I sometimes forget that so many people’s view of personal training is that it’s just “hard workouts”. 

Unfortunately, that’s likely because it’s a largely unregulated industry out there and not all trainers are created equally.

A good trainer is far less concerned about giving you a “hard workout” than they are about giving you a workout that meets your own unique needs. 

#personaltrainer #nycfitness #fitnessjourney #personaltrainernyc

Happy holidays from our little family to yours ❤️ first Christmas home in New York has been a success!

A lot of people are going to be jumping into new fitness routines this week- and while that can be a wonderful thing, unfortunately a lot of times, the motivation for doing so comes from a place of guilt, shame, and caving to pressure from manipulative marketing. 

This week, I did 2022 recaps with the clients I was able to see.  I asked everyone what they were most proud of, in regards to our training sessions.  And their responses were such a great reminder that there are so many different “whys”. While most people are already looking ahead to set 2023 goals, I don’t want you to diminish how far you may have come already this year.  So, I wanted to share some for anyone who may be feeling the pressure this week.  Consistent movement from a place of a compassion can be a really amazing, life-changing thing.

I love celebrating my clients’ wins with them and I couldn’t be more proud of the amazing work we’ve done together this year!

I’d love to hear something you’re proud of yourself for this year, too ❤️👇

To anyone joining a gym this week, starting a program, or finding a new rhythm in their routine- welcome!  Im so excited for you.  You belong here.❤️

To anyone within the fitness industry using these folks as the butt of an unfunny joke in your poorly executed marketing campaigns, I have some words for you🙃.

#fitnessjourney #newyearsresolutions #fitnessindustry #personaltrainernyc

Highly requested push up video!

A few things:

▫️If you’re feeling frustrated, do keep in mind that push ups are challenging!  We love modifications here- please use them!  I adore inclines- use that elevation and don’t be afraid or embarrassed to start it HIGH and work down while you’re really mastering your plank and push up.

▫️Expect it to take TIME to work up to a full floor push up! I can’t give you an exact timeline because everyone is different, but be patient with yourself.  A modified push up still counts as a push up! You’re doing great.

▫️I’m aware there are lots of other ways to work on push ups.  I had 60 seconds of video space.  This is a (quick!) example of how I personally like to work on push ups with clients!!! Putting in this caveat because I know those comments are inevitable lol.

Any other questions about push ups?  Drop em’ below!

3 years since 2020 sounds absolutely surreal. I remember getting the call that gyms were closing on March 16th and feeling certain my career and life as I knew it were probably over.  The latter was definitely true- but certainly not in the ways I thought.  Kind of wild to think I’d never trained through a screen and didn’t even know what Zoom was yet.🙃

I hired our first trainer and launched @mfstrongnyc in December of 2019 as an entirely in-person training business- and three months later,  it was pivot or fail. 

From building a business during the pandemic, transitioning to virtual and back to in person too many times to count, moving to Brooklyn, opening our studio and moving spaces twice in 6 months, and growing a team of trainers, I’m equal parts exhausted and proud thinking about everything that’s happened. 

Nah, screw it- I’m mostly really proud 😊

#personaltrainer #smallbusinessowner #womenownedbusiness #nyctrainer #personaltrainernyc #nycfitness

“Low impact exercise” is all the rage right now!

… but a lot of people talking about it seem confused about what it actually is.

Let’s clear it up: resistance training is low impact.

Low impact isn’t limited to hot girl walks and Pilates. 

Low impact and low intensity are not the same thing.

Continue to ask questions instead of simply following trends and be wary of folks using popular buzzwords to create fear mongering - particularly, when they’re trying to sell you something. 

#personaltrainer #fitnessjourney #nyctrainer #lowimpactmovement

I’ve been wanting to share more thoughts about weight loss for awhile but I’ve been hesitant to do so.  It’s a tough conversation to have on the internet, especially when both sides of the topic can be so very loud.  Personally and professionally, my feelings have ebbed and flowed on this topic for quite some time and this is where I’ve landed. 

Inspired by a conversation earlier today, I wanted to share these thoughts. 

I am not anti-weight loss.  I AM anti-diet culture.  I am a weight-neutral fitness professional. I am pro-bodily autonomy.

Civil conversation in the comments, please 🙏☺️

Are you training in all planes of motion?
When it comes to lower body, most of us are getting quite a bit of work done in the sagittal plane (front to back- so think squats, deadlifts, and lunges) but neglecting the frontal plane (side to side).

Essentially- most of us need more lateral movement in our programs!  These lateral step ups are one of my favorite lower body lateral exercises at the moment- listen along for some helpful cues I like!

What are your favorite lateral movements for lower body?👇

That’s it.  That’s the post.

Fitness and nutrition professionals are tired 😅.

When are we going to understand that there are SO many factors that determine why someone’s body looks the way it looks- ESPECIALLY when we’re talking about the most privileged people on the planet with access to resources most of us could never dream of?

“Good form” looks different on every single body.

I’m growing a bit tired of the unsolicited form advice I’m seeing all over this app.  Though perhaps *some* is well intentioned, much of it is coming from a place of cruelty and more often, plain ignorance.  There are SO many factors to take into account- from anatomical and body mechanic variations, injuries, mobility, body shape and size, etc- that will determine how someone executes a movement.

Not to mention- there’s often a much wider range of what is “good” or “safe” when it comes to movement execution than the internet likes to admit. Our bodies are pretty damn resilient and adaptive! 

I hate to think that the concern with being “perfect” is acting as a barrier for so many when it comes to strength training.

“Perfect” doesn’t exist.  You are unique and that’s a beautiful thing ❤️

#formcheck #perfectform #strengthtraining #fitnessjourney #fitnessforbeginners #fitnessforallbodies

It’s no secret to anyone that knows me that I really can’t stand anything related to the Kardashians🙃

However, I think they do a good job of reminding us that the way someone exercises does not always correlate to the way their body looks.

Despite their lack of honesty regarding cosmetic procedures, I think we’re all QUITE aware that their bodies are *NOT* built in the gym, even though they post their workouts regularly.

We don’t need to emulate the Kardashian’s workout routines, but we can keep the same energy for any celebrity or influencer sharing their workouts.

Exercising like someone will not make you look like them.  Fame is not a credential.  And we cannot forget that both privilege and genetics also play a massive role in why celebrities might look the way they do. 

As always, be cautious about where you’re getting your fitness + wellness advice from. (Not the Kardashians, please 😭).

There’s a trend on the other app currently- it starts with an image of a thin and conventionally attractive fitness influencer with the text “you’re so lucky to have that body”.

It quickly transitions into “The luck:” with a montage of videos of workouts, cute athleisure sets, and aesthetic plates filled with brightly colored fruits and veggies.

📣📣Fitness professionals, folks who make fitness content on the internet: privilege and genetics are not dirty words.  They’re simply… things that exist. They are just as real as the hard work you’ve certainly put in.  They don’t take away from that work in any way, shape, or form.

Acknowledging their existence and the role they play in our ability to succeed in this industry is the only way forward.

Ignoring them keeps us stuck in the past.  It doesn’t help create more access to the healthy lifestyles we promote.

Most coaches have equipment preferences, which is totally fine, but it doesn’t necessarily mean it’s the “best” or only way. If you’re looking to get stronger, you can be successful with many different types of equipment.

Always remember, if someone is adamant that their way is the ONLY way, they likely have ulterior motives. 

Kettlebells, dumbbells, and barbells all have their pros and cons, but at the end of the day, all three can be great options for getting strong so long as you remain consistent and add load over time ☺️. Ultimately, all types of equipment can have their time and place and it can be fun to explore new things! Try not to overthink it and enjoy the process.

Social media is brilliant at convincing you that this one new trend is THE thing you need to change your life.

Super niche, specific, and trending does extremely well with the algorithm.  It makes for a lot of sales.  It’s not a coincidence you’ll see lots of influencers adjusting their branding to shill the fad of the moment.

It’s NOISY out there.  We can quiet it down by focusing on the big picture.  You don’t need what they’re shilling.  You need to sleep, you need to eat, to hydrate, to move your body in a way that allows for consistency.  Take care of yourself and focus on the bigger, more tangible things before you start sweating the small stuff. 🫶

When I’m feeling sad and drained, I always find comfort in a mat workout and I thought perhaps someone else might today, too- despite sharing workouts seeming a little silly at the moment.

The BS is out in full force this week.  It’s a lot😅. Remember that in this industry, unfortunately not everyone’s intentions are to help and that what you see is often not the full truth.  Stay safe out there, friends🫶🫶

I’ve learned in my time as a trainer that people have quite a bit of shame and embarrassment when it comes to seeking help in their fitness journey.  I think there’s an idea that this is something we should all just KNOW how to do.  But remember that most fitness professionals study for YEARS, through the firsthand experience of working with clients and regular continuing education courses and we STILL don’t have all the answers.  Add in all the conflicting information there is on social media- it can be overwhelming. There is so much to sort through and learn. 

At the end of the day, seeking help always demonstrates strength, not weakness. 🤍🤍

Even if you’re only doing a variation, like “30 Hard” or “75 soft”, I wouldn’t recommend it.  I promise there are better and more sustainable ways to kick off your fitness journey!
